a Streamlet app, a Cordo document, by default, you're the one responsible for that data input.

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:35.359
So I propose one solution to this, which is data contracts.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:44.720
So what is a data contract? So because I was a grad student once, of course, I look it up

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:49.519
in the dictionary. From the Oxford English Dictionary, a contract is a written or spoken

00:04:49.519 --> 00:04:56.720
agreement that's intended to be enforceable. And an agreement from the Oxford English Dictionary

00:04:56.720 --> 00:05:03.519
is harmony or accordance of opinion or feeling in a negotiated arrangement. Note that this

00:05:03.519 --> 00:05:12.160
definition does not include technology. A data contract is an agreement, not a piece of technology.

00:05:12.959 --> 00:05:15.279
So see, just like Fred from Scooby-Doo there,

00:05:16.959 --> 00:05:21.519
surprise, this is not a talk about technology. This is a talk about organizational dynamics.

00:05:23.359 --> 00:05:28.799
Nobody left for the door. Awesome. But we will talk a little bit of technology.

00:05:34.079 --> 00:05:41.760
Let's talk about what makes a good agreement between a data producer and a data consumer.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:52.559
First up, people. People are the most important part of this puzzle, of the data input puzzle.

00:05:54.399 --> 00:06:00.959
They come first always. Every data contract should be people first. And there's three main

00:06:00.959 --> 00:06:06.559
people or groups of people that you really want to put into any good agreement about data.

00:06:07.119 --> 00:06:15.600
First up, ownership. Who owns the contract? Who maintains the contract? If, let's say,

00:06:16.799 --> 00:06:21.600
somebody producing the data and somebody consuming the data disagree, who makes the call?

00:06:22.399 --> 00:06:25.839
Who decides what goes into a data contract and what's left out? That's the owner.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:32.000
The person responsible. This is what most people think about when they think data contract.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.440
The person responsible is the person who gets the call when the contract is broken.

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:40.480
When that contract, when one of the expectations of a data contract is broken,

00:06:41.679 --> 00:06:51.119
who gets the 5 a.m. call? And consultant. And consultant is usually where you,

00:06:51.119 --> 00:06:55.920
the data scientist, as the data producers come in. The people consulted for a data contract are the

00:06:55.920 --> 00:07:01.119
people using the data. Whose work depends on it. Who needs to know when the contract is broken?

00:07:01.119 --> 00:07:07.440
And just like that meme in the lower right, surprise, it's all racy all the way down.

00:07:12.959 --> 00:07:16.320
And those of you who are familiar with data contracts may be expecting this next one.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:21.679
One of the core tenants of data contracts, of a successful data contract,

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:27.760
is really well laid out expectations. That's when you, the data consumer, and the data producer

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:31.600
creating the data, come to an agreement on what form that data should take.

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:36.880
So a couple of things that you should always have in a data contract, I propose, number one,

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:42.320
a schema. That's what most people think about. The data schema is what form does the data take?

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:45.600
What columns are in the data? What data types are those columns?

00:07:46.959 --> 00:07:52.640
Valid values. Really quickly, who was in Hadley's art and production workshop on Monday?

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:59.200
Decent group. Hadley showed an example of a data input changing to a data output

00:08:00.079 --> 00:08:04.239
that had a temperature column that changed from Fahrenheit to Celsius.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:09.920
That's a great example of some valid values that you should have in a data contract. You should

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:14.320
be expecting, you should have an expectation of what values are going to go into your output.

00:08:16.559 --> 00:08:21.519
SLAs. This is super critical, especially for those of you creating very business-like

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:27.359
business-critical pieces of information. An SLA is around how often data changes.

00:08:28.399 --> 00:08:32.640
What's the expected update frequency of data? What's the expected lag time of that data?

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:36.880
It's really important to put that out because let's say you're building a Shiny app,

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:40.400
you're expecting it to be consuming daily data, and that data changes the monthly.

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:46.320
The people actually looking at that Shiny app might be taken by surprise there.

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:51.359
The interface of data, also super important. Interface is where's the data stored?

00:08:52.239 --> 00:08:59.679
Is it in the database? Is it in S3 store? How do I get it? Any needs on query performance,

00:08:59.679 --> 00:09:02.239
that's super important. If you're building a machine learning model,

00:09:02.239 --> 00:09:06.239
you need data quickly, that should be something you build out in your data contract.

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:11.760
Compliance, also super important.

00:09:11.919 --> 00:09:17.760
Super important. Most of us have worked in, most of us are probably working in

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:22.559
industries that are regulated or soon to be regulated. So does your data need to comply

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:26.799
with any regulatory requirements? Who here, show of hands, who's in healthcare?

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:36.400
HIPAA? Who here's in finance? PCI? Who here works with any sort of customer data?

00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:42.479
Most of us, GDPR. Almost all data is going to have these days some compliance behind it.

00:09:43.359 --> 00:09:47.919
So it's really important that you make sure that that is noted in your data contract,

00:09:47.919 --> 00:09:52.479
and you know what those compliance effects are going to be. If data gets deleted because

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:58.880
it needs to be deleted for compliance, that's something you should be keeping track of and

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:01.520
know that that's something your outputs can deal with.

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:06.239
And then probably most critically is interoperability. One of the great things,

00:10:06.239 --> 00:10:10.479
one of the things to look out for as you're starting to build data contracts in your workflow

00:10:11.599 --> 00:10:21.520
is, can that data contract be consumed by people and machines? So can your data inputs,

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:25.599
can your data outputs consume the output of your data contract? Can they tell if a data

00:10:25.599 --> 00:10:29.919
contract's failing? That can help you create failure statements, that can help you create

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:35.039
failure states that your users expect, and help you make sure that your outputs are always giving

00:10:35.039 --> 00:10:45.359
users a good experience. Really quick question. Now that I've kind of thrown some information at

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:50.960
you about data contracts between consumers and producers, who thinks a data contract should be

00:10:51.919 --> 00:11:00.719
built by the data consumer? A few hands. Who thinks it should be built by the data producer?

00:11:02.479 --> 00:11:09.440
A few more hands. Who thinks it should be both? The correct answer. The answer is both.

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:15.119
Data contracts should always be built collaboratively. If they're not, if you're

00:11:15.119 --> 00:11:20.239
working in a company, you join a company where you're doing data contracts or being built by

00:11:20.239 --> 00:11:25.520
one or the other, that's a red flag. Data contracts should be agreements. They should be

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:32.080
mutually agreed upon. If they're being built by just the data consumers, that's a big organizational

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:36.960
issue. That's usually, I always think of that as a cry for help. That means that we have no idea

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:42.719
what our data engineering team is doing, and we're not having a great time. If they're being built by

00:11:42.719 --> 00:11:49.200
the producers, that again is an organizational problem. That's a little bit different problem.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:53.599
Usually that means that your data products probably aren't meeting the needs of the consumer.

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:04.239
Quickly, let's talk technology. Most of you are probably familiar with data contract technology.

00:12:04.239 --> 00:12:11.280
Who here has heard of great expectations? Decent number of people. One thing I want to really

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:15.280
stress here is that data contract technology is super helpful, but it's not everything.

00:12:16.239 --> 00:12:22.400
Thinking back to the slides we did before, data contract technology is really great at enforcing

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:27.440
expectations on data. It's really good at enforcing things like schema, the valid values,

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:33.760
SLAs, really good at doing that. It's good at informing stakeholders, but it is not a substitute

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:38.960
for defined ownership and responsibility. Most of the time, data contract tech does not do a very

00:12:38.960 --> 00:12:45.760
good job of putting together defined ownership and responsibility. Data contract technology,

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:50.719
without that ownership and responsibility, is just really complicated data engineering integration

00:12:50.719 --> 00:13:01.359
tests. I really think of data contract technology in two main buckets. First off, you've got the

00:13:01.359 --> 00:13:07.919
existing framework. That's your great expectations, your soda.io. These are great frameworks. They

00:13:07.919 --> 00:13:11.919
come with a lot of advantages. You can really easily plug them into your data stores. You can

00:13:11.919 --> 00:13:18.239
really easily add, you can easily stand them up. Most of the time, some of them even come as SaaS

00:13:18.239 --> 00:13:23.919
products, but they're not without their disadvantages. They typically are single language.

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:27.520
If you're in our team, working with the Python data engineering team,

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:33.200
you may have to learn Python, and a lot of these products are death by a million yamls.

00:13:33.679 --> 00:13:37.919
Again, they don't encode that ownership and responsibility.

00:13:43.119 --> 00:13:50.000
Another, what I really want to take some time here to look at is the concept of literate data

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.440
contracts. This is something that I've introduced to a couple different teams with some pretty good

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:58.799
success. If you scan that QR code down there, it'll take you to a repo on my GitHub that shows

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:05.760
an example of a literate data contract in Cordo. A literate data contract, you can think of this

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:11.840
almost like an extension of literate programming. What it does is it encodes, it uses all of the

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:18.640
code that builds a great data contract that enforces all those expectations. Because it's

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:22.719
built into a literate programming framework, it gives you all that advantage of a literate

00:14:22.719 --> 00:14:28.479
programming framework. You can use words. You can use words to incorporate and encode

00:14:29.039 --> 00:14:33.919
that ownership and responsibility into the actual data contract itself.

00:14:34.799 --> 00:14:38.960
And not just that, because those words are usually going to be somewhere like a Git repository,

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:45.520
you can use that Git repository's tools to actually track changes. First of all,

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:49.840
you can track changes, which is great. Second of all, you can use that track change to really build

00:14:50.719 --> 00:14:56.559
consensus around a specific data contract. If you go to that repo that's linked there,

00:14:57.440 --> 00:15:03.919
I put an example there of a pull request to a data contract. Git pull requests are one of the

00:15:03.919 --> 00:15:09.440
most fantastic tools for building consensus around a data contract, for tracking the changes you're

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:13.200
putting in there, and for making sure that everyone's on the same page, that you're

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:18.239
building that organizational agreement, that everybody's bought into the data contracts concept.

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:24.400
But, just like everything else, it's not without disadvantages. The biggest disadvantage to a

00:15:24.400 --> 00:15:28.640
literate programming framework, it's more words. More words, more work.

00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:36.960
What I really want to stress here is that there is no right answer. If you're looking at adopting

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:43.520
data contracts in your organization, pick a technology that works best for you. And take,

00:15:43.679 --> 00:15:48.159
I'm hoping that this will give you some tools to really think about how to use data contracts,

00:15:48.159 --> 00:15:51.760
how to incorporate them, and how to think about different technologies, and make sure you're

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:58.719
picking the best one. So now, hopefully all of you are bought in. We're all going to start data

00:15:58.719 --> 00:16:06.080
contracts at our companies next week. I just wanted to give you a couple tools that I've found

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:08.880
through adopting data contracts at a couple different companies.

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:15.840
First up, expect resistance. Most of the time when I've been delivering data contracts,

00:16:15.840 --> 00:16:24.320
it has been as a data consumer, as a data science team lead. When you're creating data contracts,

00:16:24.320 --> 00:16:28.719
or trying to create data contracts as a data consumer, what you're really trying to do there

00:16:28.719 --> 00:16:33.520
is you're trying to move responsibility away from the organization. You're trying to move

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:43.919
responsibility upstream. There's no way around that. You're trying to put more responsibility

00:16:43.919 --> 00:16:49.039
for their outputs onto your data producing teams. And that's often an uncomfortable process.

00:16:49.679 --> 00:16:55.200
I have received a lot of messages just like these, especially the bottom right one.

00:16:55.679 --> 00:16:57.119
You want me to do more now?

00:17:00.719 --> 00:17:04.959
So one thing I'd suggest is really leading with empathy. Those of you that were in Hadley's

00:17:04.959 --> 00:17:12.880
workshop, Hadley's number one recommendation there was meet people. Meet your team. Get to know them.

00:17:14.719 --> 00:17:22.239
If you're in the office, take them to lunch. If you're remote, Zoom beers, meet and greets,

00:17:22.239 --> 00:17:26.560
any excuse you can have to meet their team is fantastic, to meet your data producers.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:33.359
And learn about their pain points. That's one of the key things. If you can show that empathy

00:17:33.359 --> 00:17:41.680
towards their pain and how data contracts might help, that can be huge. Be ready.

00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:45.599
If you ask them what their biggest pain point is, it might be you.

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:52.719
Been there. Take the note. Take the note and think about how what you can do with data contracts can

00:17:52.719 --> 00:18:00.319
help that. So just a couple general themes. I know I'm getting close on time, so I'll really

00:18:00.319 --> 00:18:05.359
speed through these. A couple general themes to think about as you're thinking about adopting

00:18:05.359 --> 00:18:12.880
data contracts. First off, articulate value. Business value is super important. Data engineers

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:17.920
typically don't do a good job, are typically very divorced from business value. So the more you can

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:26.479
articulate that, the better. And keeping it simple. Think about your goal here is to save

00:18:26.479 --> 00:18:30.479
time and build credibility. How much validation do you really need? Think about minimum viable

00:18:30.479 --> 00:18:37.439
valuation. Do you need a data contract on every single table? Probably not. Do you need a data

00:18:37.439 --> 00:18:46.479
contract to cover every column of every table? Probably not. And think about how you can simplify

00:18:46.479 --> 00:18:54.800
your data producer's lives. And with that, thank you. You scan this QR code, takes you to repo with

